Heavy rain in the area the night before--may have contibuted to this nice concentration--of Warblers.
Photos of the Pelican were obtained.  This was well documented. Didn''t record all the birds that day.

Overcast, light rain early a.m. but diminished by 8 or so to the point that didn''t have to worry much about drops on binocs.  Birding with TOS group led by Phillip Casteel and Richard Connors.  Some nice waves of warblers, lots of swallows over river.
Birding with Chris Sloan, Harold Howell, Ginger Goolsby, Ed Schneider, and Camille.  Beautiful scope looks at Henslow''s Sparrow from about 30 m.
Birding with Harry Forbes and Ronnie Moore, from TX. Met Chris Sloan there, who was doing a survey of birds there.

Birding with Harold and Ginger ''til about 3, then by self from prior to dinner.  Overcast but not raining but everything wet, creek flooding Rogers Path.--Nice look at Lincoln''s Sparrow and Nashville Warbler.

4pm-530pm.  30min owling
Mostly birded the lake edge and the lake.  Merlin flyby at the marina.  ~150 gulls seen across the lake, too far to ID.  Went there though.

2 merlin perched together.  Scoped at 25m.  Saw through scope together!  Light was fading and no info on sex. I tried to not count the same loons and grebes from Hamilton Creek.  A bunch of overlap since I was covering the same water.

The ducks came in to roost near Seven Points rec area- bufflehead and goldeneye.  Flew in in small groups to one area.  One flock of gulls in the air was led by 3500 bonies with ringers behind. Another mind-boggling flock got off the water and there could have been between 16-20k.  I am reporting a low estimate.  There was another flock roosting on the water of about 3000 ringers.  3 roosting areas seen from Cook.  Ugh.  LOTS of loons in close.  Whistled for screech owl at dusk and in 1 min got 1 bird.

The Screech owls responded about 3:50pm to a tape that Field Sparrows went bonkers too.
Also heard two screech owls calling.  They are not added to this list because I have yet to see one and didn''t want it counting as a life bird.

One adult Herring Gull, rest were imm.  A couple were massive compared to the ringers.  Didn''t have time to look real close, but there could be something else in that mix.  Probably more ring-billed gulls than reports.

Arrived early, walking out to find Chris Holt already there. Chris is a new birder, first time we've met. Later Ed Schneider and Stanley York came, followed by Stephen Zipperrer and his Dad. No sign of a Pacific Loon, but lots of coves that can't be seen from here. Didn't look anywhere else on the lake, which I had intended too. Went straight from here to the Rutherford Co Landfill site for the Iceland Gull. Beautiful day, very light wind, cold initially at about 20 F, but warmed to the 40's pretty rapidly. Very little cloud cover.
